00:46:24.970 --> 00:46:26.540
They can think you're crazy.

00:46:26.540 --> 00:46:27.730
They can't disagree
that you believe it,

00:46:27.730 --> 00:46:29.813
and that's often a good
way of introducing to say,

00:46:29.813 --> 00:46:32.890
oh, I come to think
of it like this.

00:46:32.890 --> 00:46:35.380
Steve Jobs is actually
really good about this.

00:46:35.380 --> 00:46:38.170
In his public interviews,
he'll just often

00:46:38.170 --> 00:46:39.610
answer things in that--

00:46:39.610 --> 00:46:42.236
he would answer things
in that kind of way.

00:46:42.236 --> 00:46:44.110
But one way or another,
you want to get clear

00:46:44.110 --> 00:46:47.080
really early in the
discussion, whether you say it

00:46:47.080 --> 00:46:49.030
as your own story or
whether you ask them,

00:46:49.030 --> 00:46:51.550
that they're going to
look at the full context

00:46:51.550 --> 00:46:53.390
and that human beings
are the priority.

00:46:53.390 --> 00:46:56.620
So often, I'll just
say, OK, would you--

00:46:56.620 --> 00:46:59.546
whatever they say, I am
always happy to talk about it.

00:46:59.546 --> 00:47:01.920
So they're like, I want to
talk about how a human being--

00:47:01.920 --> 00:47:03.760
how fossil fuel
executives are murdering

00:47:03.760 --> 00:47:06.210
little children and Belize
or something like that.

00:47:06.210 --> 00:47:08.560
So I go, great, let's discuss
the evidence for that.

00:47:08.560 --> 00:47:10.900
Or let's say, climate
change is doing it.

00:47:10.900 --> 00:47:14.080
Say, but, just so
we're clear, would you

00:47:14.080 --> 00:47:16.120
agree that when we're
looking at fossil fuels,

00:47:16.120 --> 00:47:18.550
we have to look
carefully at both

00:47:18.550 --> 00:47:20.394
the positives and
negatives and when

00:47:20.394 --> 00:47:21.560
we look at the alternatives?

00:47:21.560 --> 00:47:23.920
So we're not just going to
look at the positives of wind

00:47:23.920 --> 00:47:25.628
and the negatives of
fossil fuels, right?

00:47:25.628 --> 00:47:27.670
That would be biased.

00:47:27.670 --> 00:47:29.940
What's fascinating
about doing that,

00:47:29.940 --> 00:47:33.100
introducing the framework
into the conversation,

00:47:33.100 --> 00:47:38.290
is that 99% of people will agree
to it, but only 1% of people

00:47:38.290 --> 00:47:40.930
will practice it left
to their own devices.

00:47:40.930 --> 00:47:44.020
So almost in no conversation
will anybody really

00:47:44.020 --> 00:47:47.140
be even handed on their own.

00:47:47.140 --> 00:47:48.250
It's very, very rare.

00:47:48.250 --> 00:47:50.806
But if you make that
method explicit,

00:47:50.806 --> 00:47:52.180
they'll be much
more even handed.

00:47:52.180 --> 00:47:54.270
And if they're not,
you can play referee.

00:47:54.270 --> 00:47:55.960
Wait, wait, wait, I thought we
were going to talk about this.

00:47:55.960 --> 00:47:57.180
